{"title_page": "Daniel Weiss (art historian)", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Daniel H. Weiss\n| order       =\n| image       = DanWeiss photo.png\n| caption = President and CEO\n| predecessor = [[Thomas P. Campbell]]\n| successor = \n| title       = CEO of [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]<br>\n| predecessor2 = Emily Kernan Rafferty\n| successor2 = \n| title2       = President of [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Joanne V. Creighton]]\n| successor3 = [[Kimberly W. Benston]]\n| title3       = President of [[Haverford College]]\n| order4= 16th\n| predecessor4=Arthur J. Rothkopf\n| title4= President of<br />[[Lafayette College]]\n| successor4=[[Alison Byerly]]\n| birth_date  =\n| death_date  =\n| alma_mater  = [[The George Washington University]] (B.A). <br> [[Yale University]] (M.B.A) <br> [[Johns Hopkins University]] (M.A., Ph.D)\n| profession  = [[Professor]]\n| term_start2  = March 10, 2015<ref>{{cite news |title=Daniel H. Weiss Named Next President  of The Metropolitan Museum of Art |url=https://www.metmuseum.org/press/news/2015/daniel-weiss |accessdate=30 October 2018 |work=TheMet |date=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n| term_end2    = Present\n| term_start  = February 28, 2017<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/28/arts/design/met-museum-director-resigns-thomas-campbell.html|title=Metropolitan Museum\u2019s Director Resigns Under Pressure|date=28 February 2017|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n| term_end    = Present\n| term_start3  = 2013\n| term_end3    = 2015\n| term_start4=2005\n| term_end4=2013\n}}\n'''Daniel Weiss''' is an American [[art historian]] who is the president and chief executive officer of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rsmdiscovery/2017/10/30/ranking-the-worlds-most-admired-art-museums-and-what-big-business-can-learn-from-them/#223a4de33b33|title=Ranking The World's Most Admired Art Museums, And What Big Business Can Learn From Them|last=van Riel|first=Prof.dr Cees B.M.|date=October 30, 2017|work=Forbes|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nWeiss graduated from [[George Washington University]]'s [[Columbian College of Arts and Sciences]] with a B.A. in psychology and art history in 1979.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/gwucolumbian/docs/16060_gw_fall_pub_5_singles|title=GW Arts & Sciences Fall/Winter 2016|work=Issuu|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en}}</ref> In 1982 he graduated with a master's in medieval and modern art from [[Johns Hopkins University]] and subsequently, in 1985, obtained an MBA from the [[Yale School of Management]]. In 1992, he returned to Johns Hopkins and obtained a PhD in Western Medieval and Byzantine Art.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://forward.com/schmooze/216934/jewish-art-historian-takes-the-reins-at-met-museum/|title=Jewish Art Historian Takes the Reins at Met Museum|work=The Forward|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter obtaining his MBA he then joined the management consultancy Booz, Allen & Hamilton in New York. He left in 1989, to obtain his PhD degree and afterwards started working at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, where he served as history of art professor and department head from 1992 to 2001 and as dean of faculty from 2001 to 2002.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pages.jh.edu/~jhumag/1199web/divine.html|title=Johns Hopkins Magazine -- November 1999|website=pages.jh.edu|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Weiss  started serving as dean at Johns Hopkins University's [[Krieger School of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hub.jhu.edu/2015/03/17/daniel-weiss-named-metropolitan-museum-of-art-president/|title=Former Johns Hopkins student, faculty member to lead New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art|date=2015-03-17|work=The Hub|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2005 to 2013, he then served as president of [[Lafayette College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://president.lafayette.edu/daniel-weiss-biography/|title=Daniel H. Weiss Biography \u00b7 The President \u00b7 Lafayette College|website=president.lafayette.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref> In 2016, the college named their new black box theater in [[William C. Buck Hall]] for Weiss and his wife, Sandra.<ref>{{cite news |title=New College Theater Will be Named for Daniel and Sandra Weiss |url=https://liveconnected.lafayette.edu/news-events/new-college-theater-will-be-named-for-daniel-and-sandra-weiss/ |accessdate=28 November 2018 |work=liveconnected.lafayette.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New College Theater Will be Named for Daniel and Sandra Weiss \u00b7 News \u00b7 Lafayette College |url=https://news.lafayette.edu/2013/07/11/new-college-theater-will-be-named-for-daniel-and-sandra-weiss/ |accessdate=28 November 2018 |work=news.lafayette.edu |date=July 11, 2013}}</ref> From 2013 to 2015, he served as the president of [[Haverford College]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://haverfordclerk.com/president-weiss-to-step-down-in-july/|title=President Weiss to Step Down in July|last=Greifeld|first=Katie|date=March 10, 2015|work=The Clerk|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Metropolitan Museum===\n\nWeiss was appointed the president of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/11/arts/design/daniel-h-weiss-of-haverford-expected-to-be-metropolitan-museums-new-president.html|title=Metropolitan Museum of Art Names New President: Daniel Weiss|last=Kennedy|first=Randy|date=March 10, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> In 2017, he was named as the museum's president and chief executive officer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.architectmagazine.com/design/daniel-h-weiss-appointed-president-and-chief-executive-officer-of-the-met_o|title=Daniel H. Weiss Appointed President and Chief Executive Officer of The Met|last=Popera|first=Ashleigh|date=June 23, 2017|work=Architect Magazine|access-date=}}</ref> His appointment as The Met\u2019s top leader received attention in the museum community, as the higher-ranking role in a museum is traditionally the Director.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/13/arts/design/met-museum-changes-leadership-structure.html|title=Met Museum Changes Leadership Structure|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=June 13, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nDuring Weiss\u2019 tenure, the museum has set attendance records for three years straight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/museums/met-sees-highest-attendance-ever--even-with-new-admission-fees/2018/07/05/957e8eea-7a2c-11e8-80be-6d32e182a3bc_story.html|title=Met sees highest attendance ever \u2014 even with new admission fees|last=Smee|first=Sebastian|date=July 5, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> Following high operating deficits, which led to staff cuts, the Museum improved revenue and set fundraising records, and has said it will have a balanced budget by 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/16/arts/design/met-museum-annual-report.html|title=With Big Gift and Tighter Oversight, the Met Gains Solid Ground|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=November 16, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nWhen Weiss arrived at The Met, he discovered the museum faced significant operating deficits, so he chose to sequence large capital projects the Museum was planning. He moved ahead with renovations of the skylights over the European Paintings galleries, and paused the modern wing project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/11/arts/design/the-metropolitan-museum-will-delay-a-new-600-million-wing.html|title=The Metropolitan Museum Will Delay a New $600 Million Wing|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=January 11, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> After The Met made progress on balancing the budget, Weiss announced moving ahead with major renovation of galleries covering art from Africa, Oceania and the Americas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2018/11/19/the-met-rockefeller-wing-africa-oceania-americas-galleries-renovation/|title=The Met announces $70 million renovation of Africa, Oceania and Americas galleries|last=Gibson|first=Eleanor|date=November 18, 2019|work=Dezeen|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/18/arts/design/mets-leaders-move-ahead-with-modern-and-rockefeller-wings.html|title=Met\u2019s Leaders Move Ahead With Modern and Rockefeller Wings|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=November 18, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nWeiss advocated for changing The Met\u2019s admissions policy for the first time in 50 years<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.artnews.com/2018/01/04/met-charge-mandatory-25-admission-fee-towners-ending-suggested-rates/|title=Met to Charge Mandatory $25 Admission Fee to Out-Of-Towners, Ending \u2018Suggested\u2019 Rates|last=Freeman|first=Nate|date=January 4, 2018|work=Artnews|access-date=}}</ref>\u2014which was controversial, and has ended up being described as highly successful.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hyperallergic.com/420505/met-museum-president-daniel-weiss-answers-questions-about-the-new-admissions-policy/|title=Met Museum President Daniel Weiss Answers Questions About the New Admissions Policy|last=Vartanian|first=Hrag|date=January 8, 2018|work=Hyperallergic|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/arts/met-museum-attendance-revenue-year-after-imposing-fee|title=Met Museum attendance, revenue up a year after imposing fee|last=Kreinin Souccar|first=Miriam|date=January 4, 2019|work=Crain\u2019s New York Business|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/18/arts/design/met-museum-fees.html|title=Met Admission Fees Will Send $2.8 Million to Over 175 City Cultural Groups|last=Moynihan|first=Colin|date=March 18, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nWeiss was the first leader to speak out on several important issues touching museums, including the Trump administration decision to pull out of [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/12/us/politics/trump-unesco-withdrawal.html|title=U.S. Will Withdraw From Unesco, Citing Its \u2018Anti-Israel Bias\u2019|last=Harris|first=Gardiner|date=October 12, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=|last2=Erlanger|first2=Steven}}</ref> On October 12, 2017 Weiss voiced, on behalf of the museum:\n\n''\"President Trump\u2019s decision to withdraw from UNESCO undermines the historic role of the United States as a leader in this effort and weakens our position as a strong advocate for cultural preservation. Although UNESCO may be an imperfect organization, it has been an important leader and steadfast partner in this crucial work.\"<ref>\"Metropolitan Museum of Art Issues Statement Against U.S. Decision to Pull Out of UNESCO\",\nBY Alex Greenberger, 10/12/17. ''Artnews'' journal. [http://www.artnews.com/2017/10/12/metropolitan-museum-of-art-issues-statement-against-u-s-decision-to-pull-out-of-unesco/].</ref>''\n\nWeiss has also taken positions on Saudi funding,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/18/arts/design/museums-saudi-money-jamal-khashoggi.html|title=Met and Brooklyn Museums Will Not Use Saudi Money for Programs on the Middle East|last=Sopan|first=Deb|date=October 18, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> in the wake of the murder of the Washington Post journalist, and funding from the Sackler family.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/museums/as-more-museums-say-no-to-sackler-donations-family-trust-halts-its-giving/2019/03/25/83ac5ab4-4f22-11e9-88a1-ed346f0ec94f_story.html|title=As more museums say no to Sackler donations, family trust halts its giving|last=McGlone|first=Peggy|date=March 26, 2019|work=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2016, Weiss received a Distinguished Alumni Achievement Award from [[George Washington University]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2018, Weiss received an [[honorary degree]] from [[Ithaca College]],<ref>https://www.ithaca.edu/ic-news/releases/ithaca-college-to-recognize-three-with-honorary-degrees-50152/</ref> the Leadership and Society Award from the Yale School of Management,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://som.yale.edu/news/2018/11/indra-k-nooyi-80-and-daniel-h-weiss-85-honored-by-nyc-alumni-chapter|title=Indra K. Nooyi \u201980 and Daniel H. Weiss \u201985 Honored by NYC Alumni Chapter|last=|first=|date=November 20, 2018|work=Yale.edu|access-date=}}</ref> and the Centennial Medal from the Foreign Policy Association.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorksocialdiary.com/the-foreign-policy-association-celebrates-100-years/|title=The Foreign Policy Association celebrates 100 years|last=NYSD Staff|first=|date=November 5, 2018|work=New York Social Diary|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Additional affiliations and memberships ==\nWeiss serves on the Board of the [[Samuel H. Kress Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kressfoundation.org/about/trustees_staff/|title=Kress Foundation {{!}} Trustees and Staff|website=www.kressfoundation.org|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref> He is also a member of the Board of Directors of The [[Posse Foundation]], the [[Library of America]] and of the Advisory Board of the [[Yale School of Management]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytartleadersnetwork.com/ALN2018/speaker/9532/daniel-h.-weiss|title=Speaker Details: Art Leaders Network 2018|website=www.nytartleadersnetwork.com|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://som.yale.edu/community/school-leadership-boards/boards-councils/yale-som-board-of-advisors|title=Yale SOM Board of Advisors|date=2013-05-26|website=Yale School of Management|language=en|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\nWeiss has published different books and in June 2017, signed a contract with PublicAffairs for his new book \"[https://www.hachettebookgroup.com/titles/daniel-h-weiss/in-that-time/9781541773899/ In That Time: A Story of Loss and Reconciliation in the Era of Vietnam]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/26/arts/design/met-museum-daniel-weiss-vietnam-book.html|title=As if He Isn\u2019t Busy Enough: Met Museum Head to Write Book|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en}}</ref> The book will be published in November 2019.\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* ''Art and Crusade in the Age of Saint Louis''\n* ''The Book of Kings: Art, War, and the Morgan Library\u2019s Medieval Picture Bible''\n* ''France and the Holy Land''\n* ''Remaking College''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haverford.edu/college-communications/news/haverford-and-swarthmore-presidents-explore-change-and-opportunity|title=Haverford and Swarthmore Presidents Explore Change and Opportunity at Liberal Arts Colleges|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|124103}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-aca}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[List of Lafayette College people#Presidents of Lafayette College|President of Lafayette College]]\n| before = [[Arthur J. Rothkopf]]\n| after = [[Alison Byerly]]\n| years = 2006\u20132013\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[Haverford College|President of Haverford College]]\n| before = [[Joanne V. Creighton]]\n| after = [[Kimberly W. Benston]]\n| years = 2013-2015\n}}\n{{S-culture}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[File:Metropolitam Museum of Art by Simon Fieldhouse.jpg|44px]]<br/>[[List of Presidents of the Metropolitan Museum of Art|President of the Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n| years = 2015-present\n| before = Emily Kernan Rafferty\n| after = Incumbent\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Lafayette College presidents}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weiss, Daniel}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Management alumni]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University alumni]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University faculty]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Lafayette College]]\n[[Category:Lafayette College trustees]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:Columbian College of Arts and Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Haverford College]]\n[[Category:American art historians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Daniel H. Weiss\n| order       =\n| image       = DanWeiss photo.png\n| caption = President and CEO\n| predecessor = [[Thomas P. Campbell]]\n| successor = \n| title       = CEO of [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]<br>\n| predecessor2 = Emily Kernan Rafferty\n| successor2 = \n| title2       = President of [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Joanne V. Creighton]]\n| successor3 = [[Kimberly W. Benston]]\n| title3       = President of [[Haverford College]]\n| order4= 16th\n| predecessor4=Arthur J. Rothkopf\n| title4= President of<br />[[Lafayette College]]\n| successor4=[[Alison Byerly]]\n| birth_date  =\n| death_date  =\n| alma_mater  = [[The George Washington University]] (B.A). <br> [[Yale University]] (M.B.A) <br> [[Johns Hopkins University]] (M.A., Ph.D)\n| profession  = [[Professor]]\n| term_start2  = March 10, 2015<ref>{{cite news |title=Daniel H. Weiss Named Next President  of The Metropolitan Museum of Art |url=https://www.metmuseum.org/press/news/2015/daniel-weiss |accessdate=30 October 2018 |work=TheMet |date=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n| term_end2    = Present\n| term_start  = February 28, 2017<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/28/arts/design/met-museum-director-resigns-thomas-campbell.html|title=Metropolitan Museum\u2019s Director Resigns Under Pressure|date=28 February 2017|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n| term_end    = Present\n| term_start3  = 2013\n| term_end3    = 2015\n| term_start4=2005\n| term_end4=2013\n}}\n'''Daniel Weiss''' is an American [[art historian]] who is the president and chief executive officer of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rsmdiscovery/2017/10/30/ranking-the-worlds-most-admired-art-museums-and-what-big-business-can-learn-from-them/#223a4de33b33|title=Ranking The World's Most Admired Art Museums, And What Big Business Can Learn From Them|last=van Riel|first=Prof.dr Cees B.M.|date=October 30, 2017|work=Forbes|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nWeiss graduated from [[George Washington University]]'s [[Columbian College of Arts and Sciences]] with a B.A. in psychology and art history in 1979.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/gwucolumbian/docs/16060_gw_fall_pub_5_singles|title=GW Arts & Sciences Fall/Winter 2016|work=Issuu|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en}}</ref> In 1982 he graduated with a master's in medieval and modern art from [[Johns Hopkins University]] and subsequently, in 1985, obtained an MBA from the [[Yale School of Management]]. In 1992, he returned to Johns Hopkins and obtained a PhD in Western Medieval and Byzantine Art.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://forward.com/schmooze/216934/jewish-art-historian-takes-the-reins-at-met-museum/|title=Jewish Art Historian Takes the Reins at Met Museum|work=The Forward|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter obtaining his MBA he then joined the management consultancy Booz, Allen & Hamilton in New York. He left in 1989, to obtain his PhD degree and afterwards started working at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, where he served as history of art professor and department head from 1992 to 2001 and as dean of faculty from 2001 to 2002.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pages.jh.edu/~jhumag/1199web/divine.html|title=Johns Hopkins Magazine -- November 1999|website=pages.jh.edu|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Weiss  started serving as dean at Johns Hopkins University's [[Krieger School of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hub.jhu.edu/2015/03/17/daniel-weiss-named-metropolitan-museum-of-art-president/|title=Former Johns Hopkins student, faculty member to lead New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art|date=2015-03-17|work=The Hub|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2005 to 2013, he then served as president of [[Lafayette College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://president.lafayette.edu/daniel-weiss-biography/|title=Daniel H. Weiss Biography \u00b7 The President \u00b7 Lafayette College|website=president.lafayette.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref> In 2016, the college named their new black box theater in [[William C. Buck Hall]] for Weiss and his wife, Sandra.<ref>{{cite news |title=New College Theater Will be Named for Daniel and Sandra Weiss |url=https://liveconnected.lafayette.edu/news-events/new-college-theater-will-be-named-for-daniel-and-sandra-weiss/ |accessdate=28 November 2018 |work=liveconnected.lafayette.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New College Theater Will be Named for Daniel and Sandra Weiss \u00b7 News \u00b7 Lafayette College |url=https://news.lafayette.edu/2013/07/11/new-college-theater-will-be-named-for-daniel-and-sandra-weiss/ |accessdate=28 November 2018 |work=news.lafayette.edu |date=July 11, 2013}}</ref> From 2013 to 2015, he served as the president of [[Haverford College]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://haverfordclerk.com/president-weiss-to-step-down-in-july/|title=President Weiss to Step Down in July|last=Greifeld|first=Katie|date=March 10, 2015|work=The Clerk|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Metropolitan Museum===\n\nWeiss was appointed the president of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/11/arts/design/daniel-h-weiss-of-haverford-expected-to-be-metropolitan-museums-new-president.html|title=Metropolitan Museum of Art Names New President: Daniel Weiss|last=Kennedy|first=Randy|date=March 10, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> In 2017, he was named as the museum's president and chief executive officer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.architectmagazine.com/design/daniel-h-weiss-appointed-president-and-chief-executive-officer-of-the-met_o|title=Daniel H. Weiss Appointed President and Chief Executive Officer of The Met|last=Popera|first=Ashleigh|date=June 23, 2017|work=Architect Magazine|access-date=}}</ref> His appointment as The Met\u2019s top leader received attention in the museum community, as the higher-ranking role in a museum is traditionally the Director.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/13/arts/design/met-museum-changes-leadership-structure.html|title=Met Museum Changes Leadership Structure|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=June 13, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nDuring Weiss\u2019 tenure, the museum has set attendance records for three years straight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/museums/met-sees-highest-attendance-ever--even-with-new-admission-fees/2018/07/05/957e8eea-7a2c-11e8-80be-6d32e182a3bc_story.html|title=Met sees highest attendance ever \u2014 even with new admission fees|last=Smee|first=Sebastian|date=July 5, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> Following high operating deficits, which led to staff cuts, the Museum improved revenue and set fundraising records, and has said it will have a balanced budget by 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/16/arts/design/met-museum-annual-report.html|title=With Big Gift and Tighter Oversight, the Met Gains Solid Ground|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=November 16, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nWhen Weiss arrived at The Met, he discovered the museum faced significant operating deficits, so he chose to sequence large capital projects the Museum was planning. He moved ahead with renovations of the skylights over the European Paintings galleries, and paused the modern wing project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/11/arts/design/the-metropolitan-museum-will-delay-a-new-600-million-wing.html|title=The Metropolitan Museum Will Delay a New $600 Million Wing|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=January 11, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> After The Met made progress on balancing the budget, Weiss announced moving ahead with major renovation of galleries covering art from Africa, Oceania and the Americas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2018/11/19/the-met-rockefeller-wing-africa-oceania-americas-galleries-renovation/|title=The Met announces $70 million renovation of Africa, Oceania and Americas galleries|last=Gibson|first=Eleanor|date=November 18, 2019|work=Dezeen|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/18/arts/design/mets-leaders-move-ahead-with-modern-and-rockefeller-wings.html|title=Met\u2019s Leaders Move Ahead With Modern and Rockefeller Wings|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=November 18, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nWeiss advocated for changing The Met\u2019s admissions policy for the first time in 50 years<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.artnews.com/2018/01/04/met-charge-mandatory-25-admission-fee-towners-ending-suggested-rates/|title=Met to Charge Mandatory $25 Admission Fee to Out-Of-Towners, Ending \u2018Suggested\u2019 Rates|last=Freeman|first=Nate|date=January 4, 2018|work=Artnews|access-date=}}</ref>\u2014which was controversial, and has ended up being described as highly successful.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hyperallergic.com/420505/met-museum-president-daniel-weiss-answers-questions-about-the-new-admissions-policy/|title=Met Museum President Daniel Weiss Answers Questions About the New Admissions Policy|last=Vartanian|first=Hrag|date=January 8, 2018|work=Hyperallergic|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/arts/met-museum-attendance-revenue-year-after-imposing-fee|title=Met Museum attendance, revenue up a year after imposing fee|last=Kreinin Souccar|first=Miriam|date=January 4, 2019|work=Crain\u2019s New York Business|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/18/arts/design/met-museum-fees.html|title=Met Admission Fees Will Send $2.8 Million to Over 175 City Cultural Groups|last=Moynihan|first=Colin|date=March 18, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nWeiss was the first leader to speak out on several important issues touching museums, including the Trump administration decision to pull out of [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/12/us/politics/trump-unesco-withdrawal.html|title=U.S. Will Withdraw From Unesco, Citing Its \u2018Anti-Israel Bias\u2019|last=Harris|first=Gardiner|date=October 12, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=|last2=Erlanger|first2=Steven}}</ref> On October 12, 2017 Weiss voiced, on behalf of the museum:\n\n''\"President Trump\u2019s decision to withdraw from UNESCO undermines the historic role of the United States as a leader in this effort and weakens our position as a strong advocate for cultural preservation. Although UNESCO may be an imperfect organization, it has been an important leader and steadfast partner in this crucial work.\"<ref>\"Metropolitan Museum of Art Issues Statement Against U.S. Decision to Pull Out of UNESCO\",\nBY Alex Greenberger, 10/12/17. ''Artnews'' journal. [http://www.artnews.com/2017/10/12/metropolitan-museum-of-art-issues-statement-against-u-s-decision-to-pull-out-of-unesco/].</ref>''\n\nWeiss has also taken positions on Saudi funding,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/18/arts/design/museums-saudi-money-jamal-khashoggi.html|title=Met and Brooklyn Museums Will Not Use Saudi Money for Programs on the Middle East|last=Sopan|first=Deb|date=October 18, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> in the wake of the murder of the Washington Post journalist, and funding from the Sackler family.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/museums/as-more-museums-say-no-to-sackler-donations-family-trust-halts-its-giving/2019/03/25/83ac5ab4-4f22-11e9-88a1-ed346f0ec94f_story.html|title=As more museums say no to Sackler donations, family trust halts its giving|last=McGlone|first=Peggy|date=March 26, 2019|work=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2016, Weiss received a Distinguished Alumni Achievement Award from [[George Washington University]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2018, Weiss received an [[honorary degree]] from [[Ithaca College]],<ref>https://www.ithaca.edu/ic-news/releases/ithaca-college-to-recognize-three-with-honorary-degrees-50152/</ref> the Leadership and Society Award from the Yale School of Management,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://som.yale.edu/news/2018/11/indra-k-nooyi-80-and-daniel-h-weiss-85-honored-by-nyc-alumni-chapter|title=Indra K. Nooyi \u201980 and Daniel H. Weiss \u201985 Honored by NYC Alumni Chapter|last=|first=|date=November 20, 2018|work=Yale.edu|access-date=}}</ref> and the Centennial Medal from the Foreign Policy Association.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorksocialdiary.com/the-foreign-policy-association-celebrates-100-years/|title=The Foreign Policy Association celebrates 100 years|last=NYSD Staff|first=|date=November 5, 2018|work=New York Social Diary|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Additional affiliations and memberships ==\nWeiss serves on the Board of the [[Samuel H. Kress Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kressfoundation.org/about/trustees_staff/|title=Kress Foundation {{!}} Trustees and Staff|website=www.kressfoundation.org|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref> He is also a member of the Board of Directors of The [[Posse Foundation]], the [[Library of America]] and of the Advisory Board of the [[Yale School of Management]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytartleadersnetwork.com/ALN2018/speaker/9532/daniel-h.-weiss|title=Speaker Details: Art Leaders Network 2018|website=www.nytartleadersnetwork.com|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://som.yale.edu/community/school-leadership-boards/boards-councils/yale-som-board-of-advisors|title=Yale SOM Board of Advisors|date=2013-05-26|website=Yale School of Management|language=en|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\nWeiss has published different books and in June 2017, signed a contract with PublicAffairs for his new book \"[https://www.hachettebookgroup.com/titles/daniel-h-weiss/in-that-time/9781541773899/ In That Time: A Story of Loss and Reconciliation in the Era of Vietnam]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/26/arts/design/met-museum-daniel-weiss-vietnam-book.html|title=As if He Isn\u2019t Busy Enough: Met Museum Head to Write Book|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en}}</ref> The book will be published in November 2019.\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* ''Art and Crusade in the Age of Saint Louis''\n* ''The Book of Kings: Art, War, and the Morgan Library\u2019s Medieval Picture Bible''\n* ''France and the Holy Land''\n* ''Remaking College''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haverford.edu/college-communications/news/haverford-and-swarthmore-presidents-explore-change-and-opportunity|title=Haverford and Swarthmore Presidents Explore Change and Opportunity at Liberal Arts Colleges|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|124103}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-aca}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[List of Lafayette College people#Presidents of Lafayette College|President of Lafayette College]]\n| before = [[Arthur J. Rothkopf]]\n| after = [[Alison Byerly]]\n| years = 2006\u20132013\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[Haverford College|President of Haverford College]]\n| before = [[Joanne V. Creighton]]\n| after = [[Kimberly W. Benston]]\n| years = 2013-2015\n}}\n{{S-culture}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[File:Metropolitam Museum of Art by Simon Fieldhouse.jpg|44px]]<br/>[[List of Presidents of the Metropolitan Museum of Art|President of the Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n| years = 2015-present\n| before = Emily Kernan Rafferty\n| after = Incumbent\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n